b'' b'accounts of anti-armenian human right violations in azerbaijan b'prelude to current events in nagorno-karabakh' b'' b'+---------------------------------------------------------------------+' b'| b'| i said that on february when those people were streaming down b'| our street, they were shouting, "long live turkey!" and "glory to b'| turkey!" and during the trial i said to that ismailov, "what does b'| that mean, \'glory to turkey\'?" i still don\'t understand what turkey b'| has to do with this, we live in the soviet union. that turkey told b"| you to or is going to help you kill armenians? i still don't b'| understand why "glory to turkey!" i asked that question twice and b'| got no answer no one answered me b'| b'+---------------------------------------------------------------------+' b'' b'deposition of emma setrakovna sargisian' b'' b'born b'cook' b'sumgait emergency hospital' b'' b'resident at building apartment b'block b'sumgait [azerbaijan]' b'' b'' b"to this day i can't understand why my husband, an older man, was killed. what" b"was he killed for. he hadn't hurt anyone, hadn't said any word he oughtn't" b'have. why did they kill him? i want to find out--from here, from there, from' b'the government--why my husband was killed.' b'' b'on the 27th, when i returned from work--it was a saturday--my son was at home.' b'he doesn\'t work. i went straight to the kitchen, and he called me, "mamma, is' b'there a soccer game?" there were shouts from lenin street. that\'s where we' b'lived. i say, "i don\'t know, igor, i haven\'t turned on the tv." he looked' b'again and said, "mamma, what\'s going on in the courtyard?!" i look and see so' b"many people, it's awful, marching, marching, there are hundreds, thousands," b'you can\'t even tell how many there are. they\'re shouting, "down with the' b'armenians! kill the armenians! tear the armenians to pieces!" my god, why is' b'that happening, what for? i had known nothing at that point. we lived together' b'well, in friendship, and suddenly something like this. it was completely' b'unexpected. and they were shouting, "long live turkey!" and they had flags,' b"and they were shouting. there was a man walking in front well dressed, he's" b'around or in a gray raincoat. he is walking and saying something, i' b"can't make it out through the vent window. he is walking and saying something," b'and the children behind him are shouting, "tear the armenians to pieces!" and' b'"down with the armenians!" they shout it again, and then shout, "hurrah!" the' b'people streamed without end, they were walking in groups, and in the groups i' b'saw that there were women, too. i say, "my god, there are women there too!"' b'and my son says, "those aren\'t women, mamma, those are bad women." well we' b"didn't look a long time. they were walking and shouting and i was afraid, i" b"simply couldn't sit still. i went out onto the balcony, and my azerbaijani" b'neighbor is on the other balcony, and i say, "khalida, what\'s going on, what' b'happened?" she says, "emma, i don\'t know, i don\'t know, i don\'t know what' b'happened." well she was quite frightened too. they had these white sticks,' b"each second or third one had a white rod. they're waving the rods above their" b"heads as they walk, and the one who's out front, like a leader, he has a white" b'stick too. well maybe it was an armature shaft, but what i saw was white, i' b"don't know." b'' b'my husband got home or minutes later. he comes home and i say, "oh' b'dear, i\'m frightened, they\'re going to kill us i bet." and he says, "what are' b'you afraid of, they\'re just children." i say, "everything that happens comes' b'from children." there had been and 16-year kids from the technical and' b'vocational school. "don\'t fear," he said, "it\'s nothing, nothing all that' b'bad." he didn\'t eat, he just lay on the sofa. and just then on television they' b'broadcast that two azerbaijanis had been killed in karabakh, near askeran.' b"when i heard that i couldn't settle down at all, i kept walking here and" b'there and i said, "they\'re going to kill us, the azerbaijanis are going to' b'kill us." and he says, "don\'t be afraid." then we heard--from the central' b"square, there are women shouting near near the stage, well, they're shouting" b'different things, and you couldn\'t hear every well. i say, "you speak' b'azerbaijani well, listen to what they\'re saying." he says "close the window' b'and go to bed, there s nothing happening there." he listened a bit and then' b'closed the window and went to bed, and told us, "come on, go to sleep, it\'s' b'nothing." sleep, what did he mean sleep? my son and i stood at the window' b"until two in the morning watching. well he's sick, and all of this was" b'affecting him. i say, "igor, you go to bed, i\'m going to go to bed in a minute' b'too." he went and i sat at the window until three, and then went to bed.' b'things had calmed down slightly.' b'' b'the 28th, sunday, was my day off. my husband got up and said, "come on, emma,' b'get up." i say, "today\'s my day off, let me rest." he says, "aren\'t you going' b'to make me some tea?" well i felt startled and got up, and said, "where are' b'you going?" he says, "i\'m going out, i have to." i say, "can you really go' b"outside on a day like today? don't go out, for god's sake. you never listen to" b"me, i know, and you're not going to listen to me now, but at least don't take" b'the car out of the garage, go without the car." and he says, "come on, close' b'the door!" and then on the staircase he muttered something, i couldn\'t make it' b'out, he probably said "coward" or something.' b'' b'i closed the door and he left. and i started cleaning picking things up' b"around the house everything seemed quiet until one o'clock in the after-" b'noon, but at the bus station, my neighbor told me, cars were burning. i said,' b'"khalida, was it our car?" she says, "no, no, emma, don\'t be afraid, they' b"were government cars and zhigulis.'' our car is a gaz-21 volga. and i waited," b"it was four o'clock, five o'clock and when he wasn't home at seven i" b'said, "oh, they\'ve killed shagen!"' b'' b"tires are burning in town, there's black smoke in town, and i'm afraid, i'm" b"standing on the balcony and i'm all my whole body is shaking. my god," b"they've probably killed him! so basically i waited like that until ten" b"o'clock and he still hadn't come home. and i'm afraid to go out. at ten" b"o'clock i look out: across from our building is a building with a bookstore," b'and from upstairs, from the second floor, everything is being thrown outside.' b"i'm looking out of one window and igor is looking out of the other, and i" b"don't want him to see this, and he, as it turns out, doesn't want me to see" b'it. we wanted to hide it from one another. i joined him. "mamma," he says,' b'"look what they\'re doing over there!" they were burning everything, and there' b'were police standing there, or of them, maybe twenty policemen standing' b'on the side, and the crowd is on the other side, and two or three people are' b'throwing everything down from the balcony. and one of the ones on the balcony' b'is shouting, "what are you standing there for, burn it!" when they threw the' b'television, wow, it was like a bomb! our neighbor on the third floor came out' b'on her balcony and shouted, "why are you doing that, why are you burning those' b'things, those people saved with such difficulty to buy those things for their' b'home. why are you burning them?" and from the courtyard they yell at her, "go' b"inside, go inside! instead why don't you tell us if they are any of them in" b'your building or not?" they meant armenians, but they didn\'t say armenians,' b'they said, "of them." she says, "no, no, no, none!" then she ran downstairs to' b'our place, and says, "emma, emma, you have to leave!" i say, "they\'ve killed' b"shagen anyway, what do we have to live for? it won't be living for me without" b'shagen. let them kill us, too!" she insists, saying, "emma, get out of here,' b"go to khalida's, and give me the key. when they come i'll say that it's my" b'daughter\'s apartment, that they\'re off visiting someone." i gave her the key' b'and went to the neighbor\'s, but i couldn\'t endure it. i say, "igor, you stay' b'here, i\'m going to go downstairs, and see, maybe papa\'s papa\'s there."' b'' b'meanwhile, they were killing the two brothers, alik and valery [albert and' b'valery avanesians; see the accounts of rima avanesian and alvina baluian], in' b"the courtyard. there is a crowd near the building, they're shouting, howling," b"and i didn't think that they were killing at the time. alik and valery lived" b'in the corner house across from ours. when i went out into the courtyard i saw' b'an azerbaijani, our neighbor, a young man about years old. i say, "madar,' b"uncle shagen's gone, let's go see, maybe he's dead in the garage or near the" b'garage, let\'s at least bring the corpse into the house. "he shouts, "aunt' b"emma, where do you think you're going?! go back into the house, i'll look for" b'him." i say, "something will happen to you, too, because of me, no, madar,' b'i\'m coming too." well he wouldn\'t let me go all the same, he says, "you stay' b'here with us, i\'m go look." he went and looked, and came back and said, "aunt' b'emma, there\'s no one there, the garage is closed. "madar went off again and' b'then returned and said, "aunt emma, they\'re already killed alik, and valery\'s' b'there wheezing."' b'' b'madar wanted to go up to him, but those scoundrels said, "don\'t go near him,' b'or we\'ll put you next to him." he got scared--he\'s young--and came back and' b'said, "i\'m going to go call, maybe an ambulance will come, at least to take' b'alik, maybe he\'ll live they grew up together in our courtyard, they' b'knew each other well, they had always been on good terms. he went to call, but' b'not a single telephone worked, they had all been shut off. he call